SIMPLE: falsify
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Falsify
<hw>Fal"si*fy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Falsified</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Falsifying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>falsus</ets>
false + <ets>-ly</ets>: cf. F. <ets>falsifier</ets>. See <er>False</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make false; to represent
falsely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Irish bards use to forge and <qex>falsify</qex> everything as
they list, to please or displease any man.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To counterfeit; to forge; <as>as, to
<ex>falsify</ex> coin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To prove to be false, or untrustworthy; to confute;
to disprove; to nullify; to make to appear false.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By how much better than my word I am,⟦br⟧
By so much shall I <qex>falsify</qex> men's hope.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jews and Pagans united all their endeavors, under Julian the
apostate, to baffle and <qex>falsify</qex> the prediction.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To violate; to break by falsehood; <as>as, to
<ex>falsify</ex> one's faith or word</as>.</def> <rj><au>Sir P.
Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To baffle or escape; <as>as, to <ex>falsify</ex> a
blow</as>.</def> <rj><au>Butler.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To avoid or defeat; to prove false,
as a judgment.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Equity)</fld> <def>To show, in accounting, (an inem
of charge inserted in an account) to be wrong.</def> <rj><au>Story.
Daniell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To make false by multilation or addition; to tamper
with; <as>as, to <ex>falsify</ex> a record or document</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Falsify</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Falsify
<hw>Fal"si*fy</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To tell lies; to violate the
truth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is absolutely and universally unlawful to lie and
<qex>falsify</qex>.</q>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>South.</q>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Falsism</ent>⟦br⟧
